# New Commands Learned

## 1. grep

The `grep` command searches for specific text or patterns inside files.

### Syntax

```bash
grep [options] "pattern" filename
```

### Example

```bash
grep "ERROR" app.log
```

This displays all lines containing the word **ERROR**.

### Useful Options

| Option | Description |
|---------|-------------|
| `-w` | Match the whole word only |
| `-i` | Ignore case (case-insensitive) |
| `-E` | Enable extended regular expressions |

### Example

```bash
grep -w "ERROR" app.log
```

---

## Creating an Error Report

Save matching log entries into a new file.

```bash
grep -w "ERROR" app.log > error_report.txt
```

Here:

- `grep` searches for the pattern.
- `>` redirects the output to a file.

---

## Appending More Information

Add additional output to an existing report.

```bash
grep -w "worker_processes" nginx.conf >> error_report.txt
```

The `>>` operator appends data without overwriting the file.

